# Create a correlation matrix using Pearson correlation coefficient
pearson_correlation_matrix = df[['votes', 'budget', 'score', 'gross']].corr(method='pearson')

# Plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(pearson_correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', linewidths=.5)
plt.title('Pearson Correlation Matrix')
plt.show()
In [34]:
# Scatter plot for 'budget' vs 'gross' with movie names
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.scatter(df['budget'], df['gross'], alpha=0.5)

# Annotate points with movie names
for i, txt in enumerate(df['name']):
    plt.annotate(txt, (df['budget'].iloc[i], df['gross'].iloc[i]), fontsize=8, alpha=0.7)

plt.title('Scatter Plot: Budget vs Gross with Movie Names')
plt.xlabel('Budget')
plt.ylabel('Gross')
plt.show()

In [37]:
# Set the number of annotations to display
num_annotations = 10  # Adjust as needed

# Scatter plot for 'budget' vs 'gross' with the filtered DataFrame
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.scatter(filtered_df['budget'], filtered_df['gross'], alpha=0.5)

# Annotate a subset of points with movie names
for i, txt in enumerate(filtered_df['name'].iloc[:num_annotations]):
    plt.annotate(txt, (filtered_df['budget'].iloc[i], filtered_df['gross'].iloc[i]), fontsize=8, alpha=0.7)

plt.title(f'Scatter Plot: Budget vs Gross (Excluding Outliers) with {num_annotations} Annotations')
plt.xlabel('Budget')
plt.ylabel('Gross')
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Budget and Gross (0.687292): This positive correlation coefficient indicates a strong positive relationship between the 'budget' and 'gross' columns. 
In other words, as the budget of a movie increases, there is a tendency for the gross revenue to increase as well.

# Sort the directors by average gross revenue in descending order

In [57]:
# Choose the top N genres based on your preference
top_genres = df['genre'].value_counts().head(5).index

# Filter the DataFrame for the top genres
filtered_df_by_genre = df[df['genre'].isin(top_genres)]

# Create subplots for each genre
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))

for i, genre in enumerate(top_genres, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 3, i)  # Adjust the subplot layout based on the number of genres
    genre_data = filtered_df_by_genre[filtered_df_by_genre['genre'] == genre]
    sns.scatterplot(x='budget', y='gross', data=genre_data, alpha=0.7)
    plt.title(f'{genre} - Budget vs. Gross')
    plt.xlabel('Budget')
    plt.ylabel('Gross')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [58]:
# Choose the top N genres based on your preference
top_genres = df['genre'].value_counts().head(5).index

# Filter the DataFrame for the top genres
filtered_df_by_genre = df[df['genre'].isin(top_genres)]

# Plot scatter plot for budget vs. gross with colored points for each genre
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.scatterplot(x='budget', y='gross', hue='genre', data=filtered_df_by_genre, palette='viridis', alpha=0.7)

# Move the legend outside the plot
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')

plt.title('Scatter Plot: Budget vs. Gross by Genre')
plt.xlabel('Budget')
plt.ylabel('Gross')
plt.show()
